<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: There was like the hide and seek, and the bird watching, um, what else, the painting, the dancing, and the art, and you were able to do all those things with just a, like with your board.

895
00:44:31.679 --> 00:44:35.579
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So it just showed so many, how many different activities you could do with that.

896
00:44:35.579 --> 00:44:37.860
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But that little board.

897
00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:39.199
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

898
00:44:39.199 --> 00:44:41.179
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, you talk about the frustration.

899
00:44:41.179 --> 00:44:50.000
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's very true because sometimes you'll be like, oh, maybe this will be the thing to tell them what I'm wanting to tell them and they'll respond in a way that's like, no, that's not.

900
00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:50.719
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: what I meant.

901
00:44:50.719 --> 00:44:52.639
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like I get why you said that, right?

902
00:44:52.639 --> 00:44:56.960
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I get why you responded to what I gave you in the way that I did, but that's not why I wanted to tell you.

903
00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:58.579
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's not how I wanted you to respond.

904
00:44:58.579 --> 00:45:02.360
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And then you have to be like, oh, well, what do I what do I actually want to tell you?

905
00:45:02.360 --> 00:45:21.800
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Um, and I mean, it's a little bit different for us, me, because, um, so Nathan is, um, less, he, his understanding of things is less than the character in the game, certainly, and many people who would use communications boards.

906
00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:17.900
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

907
00:45:22.039 --> 00:45:29.119
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Nathan isn't like Nathan can't how he won't, he's unlikely to ever be able to talk realistically.

908
00:45:29.119 --> 00:45:33.199
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And it's not something that a speech therapist can fix.

909
00:45:33.199 --> 00:45:34.280
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Trust me, we've tried.

910
00:45:34.280 --> 00:45:38.780
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: His it's his understanding that's often the issue.

911
00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:35.400
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Right.

912
00:45:35.400 --> 00:45:36.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

913
00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:41.599
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: rather than necessarily his communication.

914
00:45:39.500 --> 00:45:40.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

915
00:45:41.599 --> 00:45:45.380
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's actually surprisingly good at telling you what he wants when he wants to tell you what he wants.

916
00:45:45.380 --> 00:45:53.480
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: The problem is that obviously it's like other people understanding what he's communicating is quite difficult.

917
00:45:53.480 --> 00:46:15.559
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But yeah, the idea of having like complex sentences that you're trying to like tell somebody with the symbols is absolutely the case for a lot of people who can't talk, but certainly for us, that's less of a thing because Nathan is less trying to explain feelings and thoughts and stuff and is more trying to say, I want food.

918
00:46:15.559 --> 00:46:16.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I want to go out.

919
00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:22.699
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I want this, I want that, like it's it's about what he needs and what he wants in much more simplistic terms.

920
00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:18.960
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Right.

921
00:46:23.539 --> 00:46:42.980
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: The idea of, obviously, a mental age is a bit wishy-washy and a bit complicated, but, you know, his it can sometimes be useful for people and that his, you know, mental age is is often kind of like of a toddler.

922
00:46:42.980 --> 00:47:02.539
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's, you know, just very simplistic in a lot of ways, which is, you know, you know, we love him for who he is, but can, I think, make things even more complicated than that sort of thing because he's not only trying to explain what he's saying, he's trying to understand what we're saying as well because there are.

923
00:47:02.539 --> 00:47:12.079
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He will understand certain words and phrases and what they collate to, but he will like fixate on specific words in a sentence.

924
00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:12.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

925
00:47:12.079 --> 00:47:22.699
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So you can't be like, uh, you can't say certain things in together because you will think you're tasting something else, if that makes sense.

926
00:47:22.500 --> 00:47:30.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay, yeah, it's very, very basic like, you can't have a complex thought, like, it would be taken literally.

927
00:47:29.500 --> 00:47:37.780
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, I think it's hard to know because he can't communicate in ways to explain this, but I suspect he has more complicated thoughts.

928
00:47:33.500 --> 00:47:34.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: What's it?

929
00:47:37.780 --> 00:47:40.900
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's more like the language part of it.

930
00:47:40.900 --> 00:47:52.420
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: where even when we're talking about things, he will be like, if you say, um, I'm trying to think, he's gained a lot over the last few years.

931
00:47:52.420 --> 00:47:55.420
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So the examples that I used to use don't work anymore, right?

932
00:47:55.420 --> 00:48:00.940
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like a couple of years ago, he wouldn't understand the idea of we're doing this, then we're doing that.

933
00:48:00.940 --> 00:48:10.000
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He would just assume that we're doing them like both at the same time because you've like mentioned both things he's thinking about both things and he will decide in his head.

934
00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:06.340
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

935
00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:12.760
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: We're doing one of the things you said.

936
00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:14.619
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And if you say we're doing them in this order.

937
00:48:14.619 --> 00:48:17.500
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: That doesn't mean he's going to understand the order, right?

938
00:48:17.500 --> 00:48:22.840
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Because that communication of this, then that is very hard, certainly was very hard.

939
00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:18.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Right.

940
00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:23.980
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's much better than that now.

941
00:48:23.980 --> 00:48:26.139
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: We're quite good at saying we're doing this, then we're doing that.

942
00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:26.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

943
00:48:26.139 --> 00:48:27.940
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's much better understanding that now.

944
00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:29.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Good, good.

945
00:48:28.119 --> 00:48:31.719
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But yeah, it's things like that, right?

946
00:48:31.719 --> 00:48:33.340
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like things that we take for granted.

947
00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:33.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

948
00:48:33.340 --> 00:48:39.760
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Even with like, you know, I have a three-year-old nephew, he understands certain things like that.

949
00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:43.360
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He might be a, you know, moaning about it.

950
00:48:43.360 --> 00:48:45.519
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He might not want it, but he will understand it.

951
00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:45.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I don't.

952
00:48:45.519 --> 00:48:50.440
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: In a lot of cases with Nathan, he just, he just won't understand it.

953
00:48:50.440 --> 00:48:55.420
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And sometimes, like one of the things that's really difficult for him is like negation, right?

954
00:48:55.420 --> 00:49:03.820
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Saying not this and he'll hear, he'll hear, when you say not this, he'll hear this and he'll think that he's getting this, but you said not this.

955
00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:57.840
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

956
00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:09.039
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So, like, we have to like make, like, if he asks for something and we can't have that.

957
00:49:09.039 --> 00:49:12.880
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: We say no or not now, and he will understand then that that's not.

958
00:49:12.880 --> 00:49:17.260
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But if you say, oh, like if he asks for some sweets and he's had too many sweets.

959
00:49:17.260 --> 00:49:22.480
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: If you say no sweets, he's like picking up the sweets, not necessarily the no.

960
00:49:22.480 --> 00:49:24.940
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So it's things like that.

961
00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:24.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

962
00:49:24.940 --> 00:49:34.539
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So in our case, like this game is less applicable, but it's still, I think, very useful for that frustration side of things, right?

963
00:49:34.539 --> 00:49:43.659
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Because he obviously has that even more because there's fewer symbols he can use and he can't make up like he can't make up the phrases that you can do with the board.

964
00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:35.840
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

965
00:49:43.780 --> 00:49:45.460
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Um,

966
00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:44.599
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

967
00:49:44.599 --> 00:49:46.820
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, you're pretty limited.

968
00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:53.539
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Like I try to do different combinations just to see what the result would be and Eventually I just kind of get a generic like, oh, okay.

969
00:49:53.539 --> 00:49:56.360
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I don't know if you did that yourself, but uh,

970
00:49:54.000 --> 00:50:00.000
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, I... I did, yeah, I thought that was interesting because um...

971
00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:04.019
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: There's a lot of things that will mean something in the game, right?

972
00:50:04.019 --> 00:50:15.059
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like you'll be like, oh, uh, if you say just, you know, one of the one of the things you have to do in the game is you have to help uh, find one of the characters charms that they've lost.

973
00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:21.539
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so you have to go and and ask people if they've seen it.

974
00:50:21.539 --> 00:50:24.900
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And the way you're doing that is by asking for help.

975
00:50:24.900 --> 00:50:28.679
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But if you just go up to someone and say help, they're like, oh, what do you need help with?

976
00:50:28.679 --> 00:50:28.860
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: right

977
00:50:28.860 --> 00:50:29.820
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Because they don't know.

978
00:50:29.820 --> 00:50:30.539
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: You're not telling them.

979
00:50:30.539 --> 00:50:31.559
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: You're just saying help.

980
00:50:31.559 --> 00:50:38.039
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But if you say help and then the character's name, they will then know what you're talking about because, oh, she lost the charm, right?

981
00:50:38.039 --> 00:50:40.199
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I don't know, but ask this person sort of thing.

982
00:50:40.199 --> 00:50:48.480
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so there is some more complicated things in the game that different things will lead to different outcomes, right?

983
00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:54.420
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Just saying help means they don't know what they're asking for and saying help character means that they do.

984
00:50:54.420 --> 00:51:01.679
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But there is, as you say, that point where you just, they stop, like, there's not much they can do.

985
00:51:01.679 --> 00:51:03.719
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so they're just kind of like, 0 yeah, that's nice.

986
00:51:03.719 --> 00:51:07.260
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: You know, which is probably very realistic.

987
00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:05.280
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

988
00:51:07.500 --> 00:51:11.460
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, I think it, that is pretty accurate.

989
00:51:11.460 --> 00:51:16.980
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I remember going up to different kids and just saying feel happy and they'd be like, yay, you're happy.

990
00:51:17.159 --> 00:51:21.900
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Or feel sad and they would kind of direct you to something else, but.

991
00:51:21.900 --> 00:51:29.219
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, a lot of times when people don't quite understand what's being said, even if it's a question, they'll just go, mm-hmm.

992
00:51:29.460 --> 00:51:36.000
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And I find that was pretty accurate with the game. And I mean, they couldn't come up with infinite combinations, right?

993
00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:33.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

994
00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:41.940
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But, I bet for some, like, even for like a child that would play this game, they would feel frustrated.

995
00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:43.679
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, yeah, for sure.

996
00:51:43.679 --> 00:51:58.739
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Does that, does that, um, you don't have to get too personal if you don't want to, but does that, like, map with your experience as well, because obviously your your daughter's had more complex thoughts and understandings of things and therefore presumably would use it more like this game?

997
00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:55.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, so.

998
00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:07.820
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, so when she was, so I, my experience is not the same because she, I don't want to say she grew out of it, but she found her way through speech therapy.

999
00:52:07.820 --> 00:52:11.900
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, so, she was born with a Praxio speech.

1000
00:52:11.900 --> 00:52:14.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So, her thoughts are fully there.

1001
00:52:14.659 --> 00:52:17.960
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: It's the motor function of her mouth could not pronounce words.

1002
00:52:17.960 --> 00:52:29.239
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So, um, when we went through initial therapy, it was before she was in school, um, they basically said, don't even bother.

1003
00:52:18.500 --> 00:52:19.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Okay.

1004
00:52:29.239 --> 00:52:31.400
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Thanks, Canada healthcare.

1005
00:52:31.400 --> 00:52:35.539
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, but, um, we didn't take that for an answer.

1006
00:52:35.539 --> 00:52:42.139
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So, um, because she has older siblings, they would try really hard to communicate with her and she had a very large vocabulary.

1007
00:52:42.139 --> 00:52:50.300
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, one of the tests that they did was, uh, Just to see how, how her vocabulary pool was and she was way ahead of her age.

1008
00:52:50.300 --> 00:52:54.980
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But no one could understand what she was saying just because her mouth could not form the words properly.

1009
00:52:54.980 --> 00:53:21.380
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So once we actually found out what that was, um, we were able to do exercises, um, along the jaw, along, like with the tongue and like the placement of words and, um, but yeah, when she started kindergarten, they, we had a communication book and then we even had our teachers that were amazing, they would come up to us and say, oh, we thought that she said something different, but it turns out she was saying something way more advanced for her age.

1010
00:53:21.380 --> 00:53:26.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So they thought, for an example, for one, they were saying, she was saying, oh, this hill is very steep.

1011
00:53:26.659 --> 00:53:33.019
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But she, they couldn't understand what she said, and then they realised, oh, she's actually saying this, and that was more ahead of what.

1012
00:53:33.019 --> 00:53:35.719
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Anyway, it was so frustrating to have her, um,

1013
00:53:35.780 --> 00:53:40.639
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Her vocabulary like locked behind this physical ailment.

1014
00:53:40.639 --> 00:53:54.320
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And I, again, it's a different situation because she did work through it, but I remember when the speech therapist was saying, like, she's not going to go to a, um, not a normal school, but like just like a regular classroom.

1015
00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:54.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1016
00:53:54.320 --> 00:53:58.519
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Uh, just no hope for the future.

1017
00:53:58.519 --> 00:54:04.219
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Now, like, you cannot even tell at all. I find when she's like, when she's, yeah, I don't know.

1018
00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:03.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, I think.

1019
00:54:04.219 --> 00:54:05.900
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: It's just I get emotional about it.

1020
00:54:05.900 --> 00:54:19.639
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And I know that we're very lucky because we did go, we did like go through and she's more like, you can't really tell anymore, but, I still always think of the kids that, you know, have a different condition.

1021
00:54:19.639 --> 00:54:21.440
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I can imagine how frustrating it is.

1022
00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:23.199
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I mean, that's the thing, right?

1023
00:54:23.199 --> 00:54:27.460
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: We don't need to grade these things, right?

1024
00:54:27.460 --> 00:54:32.019
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like being non-verbal is being non-verbal, right?

1025
00:54:32.019 --> 00:54:37.480
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like not being able to verbalise your thoughts and feelings is the same no matter who you are.

1026
00:54:37.480 --> 00:54:45.280
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And yet some people will gain the ability to be able to verbalise things however they want and some will not.

1027
00:54:45.280 --> 00:54:49.000
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And that is, I think that's fine.

1028
00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:49.900
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Right?

1029
00:54:49.900 --> 00:54:51.639
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like we don't, we don't, we don't.

1030
00:54:51.639 --> 00:54:52.420
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I mean, it's not fine.

1031
00:54:52.420 --> 00:54:53.800
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's incredibly frustrating.

1032
00:54:53.800 --> 00:55:07.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Our life is very difficult because of it, but fine in so much as like just because someone has a more difficult experience with things doesn't mean that your experience with things is

1033
00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:54.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yes.

1034
00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:08.840
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: That's fair.

1035
00:55:08.840 --> 00:55:11.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: For myself, this is turning into a therapy session.

1036
00:55:11.500 --> 00:55:12.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Good.

1037
00:55:11.659 --> 00:55:19.340
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, I always, yeah, I always tried to keep it a little bit more to myself because I said, okay, well, she's walking.

1038
00:55:19.340 --> 00:55:23.480
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: She's, You know, she's not physically limited.

1039
00:55:23.480 --> 00:55:24.500
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: This is fine.

1040
00:55:24.500 --> 00:55:27.739
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Like, she'll find her way, but, yeah, no, I,

1041
00:55:27.739 --> 00:55:29.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: She doesn't even remember.

1042
00:55:29.420 --> 00:55:31.699
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Like I ask her, do you remember using your communication book?

1043
00:55:31.699 --> 00:55:32.360
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: She's like, nope.

1044
00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:34.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: That's interesting how old was she?

1045
00:55:33.679 --> 00:55:35.840
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Uh, four.

1046
00:55:35.840 --> 00:55:45.980
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So she started, yeah, when she started kindergarten, she was 4 and then halfway through junior kindergarten, she used to stop using it and it wasn't even that her speech had improved so much.

1047
00:55:45.980 --> 00:55:50.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: It's just that like her classroom was so accommodating that they understood what sounds were what.

1048
00:55:50.420 --> 00:55:54.199
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So, But then, yeah, once she started going to a different therapist.

1049
00:55:54.199 --> 00:55:58.159
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, it was all, some of it was through Zoom, which was incredibly frustrating.

1050
00:55:58.159 --> 00:55:59.119
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I cannot imagine.

1051
00:55:59.119 --> 00:56:05.719
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I felt so bad for the speech therapist because how do you keep a kid's attention through Zoom, a 4 year old.

1052
00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:04.599
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1053
00:56:04.780 --> 00:56:12.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Or even just like understanding what someone says or, you know, whatever, like, is very difficult over that sort of thing.

1054
00:56:08.719 --> 00:56:10.039
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, so she had to like.

1055
00:56:10.039 --> 00:56:11.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

1056
00:56:11.659 --> 00:56:27.619
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: She had to zoom in, like, I can't even imagine, like, what her software looked like, she had to zoom in and had to had all these like different angles of the mouth to see if she's like positioning the words a certain way, and yeah, I can't imagine how frustrating that was for all the speech language pathologists.

1057
00:56:27.619 --> 00:56:32.599
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Eventually we were able to go in person, which was a lot easier because you do it through play.

1058
00:56:32.599 --> 00:56:39.800
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, so I don't know if people may have had a different experience like before COVID with their speech therapy.

1059
00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:34.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1060
00:56:39.800 --> 00:56:53.480
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, but yeah, no, I asked her about it and I said, do you remember going to see so-and-so? And she says, oh, I remember playing. But she doesn't remember any of the exercises, which is, it's crazy how resilient kids are.

1061
00:56:53.500 --> 00:56:55.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, well, I mean, that's a success, right?

1062
00:56:54.980 --> 00:57:00.920
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And she had to do, I was, uh, a throat scope when she was or uh, no scope while she was awake.

1063
00:57:00.920 --> 00:57:04.340
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I don't know if you've ever had to do that for any of your kids.

1064
00:57:03.500 --> 00:57:04.340
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: No, I haven't.

1065
00:57:04.340 --> 00:57:05.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I don't want to.

1066
00:57:04.340 --> 00:57:07.820
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, no, I had to, I thought so, okay.

1067
00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:16.219
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: This is a completely off topic tangent, but when we went, they wanted to see if she was tongue tied or if she had like something in her throat that would like limit her ability.

1068
00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:15.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1069
00:57:16.219 --> 00:57:18.860
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So I said, oh, well, we'll just do a no scope.

1070
00:57:18.860 --> 00:57:20.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I said, okay, well let's just book the appointment.

1071
00:57:20.420 --> 00:57:21.500
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: like, nope, hold her down.

1072
00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:23.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Oh.

1073
00:57:22.159 --> 00:57:23.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1074
00:57:23.659 --> 00:57:25.760
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: They're like, yeah, she's not gonna be happy.

1075
00:57:25.760 --> 00:57:26.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1076
00:57:26.420 --> 00:57:32.059
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So then they just put it down her nose, look through, and then she got a stuffed animal from the doctor and she still has it.

1077
00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:29.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1078
00:57:31.500 --> 00:57:32.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But you know...

1079
00:57:32.059 --> 00:57:33.440
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: She's like, oh, this was from the hospital.

1080
00:57:33.440 --> 00:57:36.079
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: It's like, do you remember what we did at the hospital?

1081
00:57:36.079 --> 00:57:36.739
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: No.

1082
00:57:36.739 --> 00:57:38.960
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And probably for the best then.

1083
00:57:37.500 --> 00:57:38.760
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I'm sorry.

1084
00:57:38.760 --> 00:57:41.460
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I'm sure I'm sure it will come up in therapy in the future.

1085
00:57:44.460 --> 00:58:02.820
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, it's interesting because one of the things that we particularly struggle with is explaining to, you know, medical procedures to Nathan because obviously he has a lot of time with doctors, much more than a normal, you know, regular child, you know, most people would have many fewer.

1086
00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:01.840
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

1087
00:58:02.820 --> 00:58:05.880
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so kind of trying to explain, like, this is okay.

1088
00:58:05.880 --> 00:58:08.820
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Like you're not going to be hurt here is really hard to explain.

1089
00:58:08.820 --> 00:58:13.139
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So one of the things that he's been really difficult with over the years is dentists.

1090
00:58:13.139 --> 00:58:14.280
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's getting better.

1091
00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:14.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1092
00:58:14.280 --> 00:58:28.260
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's kind of letting them look in a bit more now, but he's they really struggled with that for a long time and also struggled with getting his teeth brushed so much so that almost every single one of his baby teeth had massive cavities in them.

1093
00:58:28.260 --> 00:58:35.940
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so, so we had, we had to, we had to take them out and he still has quite a few gaps because he's still got a few teeth that haven't come in.

1094
00:58:28.500 --> 00:58:29.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, that is a...

1095
00:58:35.940 --> 00:58:38.280
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But he...

1096
00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:37.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1097
00:58:38.280 --> 00:58:42.780
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I mean, he had to go under general anaesthetic for that because it just, like, it wouldn't have worked.

1098
00:58:42.780 --> 00:58:44.099
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He couldn't have done it.

1099
00:58:44.099 --> 00:58:46.079
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He physically would not.

1100
00:58:46.079 --> 00:58:47.639
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: he wouldn't understand these things.

1101
00:58:47.639 --> 00:58:56.159
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Um, and he, he like just removes himself from the situation if he can, like he...

1102
00:58:54.500 --> 00:58:55.099
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: For sure.

1103
00:58:55.099 --> 00:58:57.019
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Sorry, go ahead.

1104
00:58:56.159 --> 00:58:57.360
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: No, no.

1105
00:58:57.019 --> 00:59:01.940
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: You think of the dentist for even like a typical person, I'll say.

1106
00:59:01.940 --> 00:59:10.760
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I don't mean it like that, but like you lie down in a chair with a light shining in your face, glasses on, men with men and women with their masks on in your mouth.

1107
00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:05.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Mm-hmm.

1108
00:59:10.760 --> 00:59:13.039
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Like, it's scary for even like the average person.

1109
00:59:11.500 --> 00:59:12.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1110
00:59:13.039 --> 00:59:15.199
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So imagine having to explain that.

1111
00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:19.360
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: tell you the worst one they had, though, was not the dentist.

1112
00:59:19.360 --> 00:59:24.639
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It was when, um, so he loves climbing and he's generally really good and he's generally really safe.

1113
00:59:24.639 --> 00:59:27.760
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But no matter how safe you are, you're always going to fall eventually.

1114
00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:31.179
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so there was one time that he fell and cracked his head off a floor.

1115
00:59:31.179 --> 00:59:44.380
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And so we had to go to the doctor's head bleeding. And we got to the hospital and they took us through and took a look at it and it was like, yeah, okay, so we're going to have to, we're going to have to staple that.

1116
00:59:31.500 --> 00:59:32.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh my.

1117
00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:35.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Wow.

1118
00:59:44.500 --> 00:59:45.940
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh, no.

1119
00:59:45.519 --> 00:59:50.500
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And I'm like, oh, so, right.

1120
00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:49.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1121
00:59:50.920 --> 00:59:56.019
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And as you say, like, even with a typical child, that would be a difficult thing to do.

1122
00:59:56.019 --> 01:00:05.199
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But we have our, uh, you know, non-verable child who cannot understand, like there's no way we could explain that to him, right?

1123
01:00:00.500 --> 01:00:01.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yep.

1124
01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:05.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: No.

1125
01:00:05.199 --> 01:00:15.159
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So we literally just had me and and Rona, my wife, either side of him, literally just holding him down while the doctor came in and just went, kadunk, kadunk.

1126
01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:16.500
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh my goodness.

1127
01:00:15.579 --> 01:00:34.420
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It was, Possibly one of my worst days, like just the horrific face that he made, like thinking he had been, you know, um, he, you know, we, we'd just done this to him and he didn't understand why.

1128
01:00:16.500 --> 01:00:18.960
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: That's probably worse for you.

1129
01:00:22.500 --> 01:00:23.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh my god.

1130
01:00:34.420 --> 01:00:39.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He didn't know that it was so important that he had this because he had this gaping headwind.

1131
01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:40.900
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It needed to be closed.

1132
01:00:39.500 --> 01:00:40.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1133
01:00:40.900 --> 01:00:44.619
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And then the worst bit was 2 weeks later, we had to take them out.

1134
01:00:45.500 --> 01:00:47.000
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh no.

1135
01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.559
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1136
01:00:48.559 --> 01:00:52.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I was gonna ask, did he pick at it a lot or?

1137
01:00:51.500 --> 01:01:07.639
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Um, I mean, yeah, not so much that it caused huge problems, but yeah, um, that reminds me of when when he went in for his general anaesthetic for getting his teeth out, he wasn't allowed to eat for 12 hours beforehand.

1138
01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:09.079
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1139
01:01:08.119 --> 01:01:12.019
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And he just did not understand why I'm not getting any food.

1140
01:01:09.079 --> 01:01:11.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Explaining, no, you can't eat.

1141
01:01:11.420 --> 01:01:12.260
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I'm sorry.

1142
01:01:12.260 --> 01:01:13.880
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1143
01:01:13.159 --> 01:01:19.219
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Because he didn't understand, you know, and he was just like constantly being like, I need food.

1144
01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:17.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: No.

1145
01:01:19.219 --> 01:01:19.880
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I need food.

1146
01:01:19.880 --> 01:01:22.460
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So yeah, that was particularly hard.

1147
01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:22.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1148
01:01:22.460 --> 01:01:30.619
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's amazing the things you take for granted before you have to try and communicate with someone who has such a limited understanding of words.

1149
01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:26.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Honest.

1150
01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:33.760
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: It's hard person like for my work.

1151
01:01:33.760 --> 01:01:53.320
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I have some clients that, um, they have dementia or things along those lines and they'll go in for a procedure or if they fall and they need stitches and they'll, they'll pick up the stitches and they open and not to get too graphic or anything, but then you have to go back and they don't understand like why, you know, so it's, oh, I can't even imagine for your own child.

1152
01:01:53.320 --> 01:01:56.500
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But, uh, was that, was that recent?

1153
01:01:53.500 --> 01:01:54.340
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1154
01:01:54.340 --> 01:01:55.539
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's hard.

1155
01:01:56.500 --> 01:01:58.000
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Or was that?

1156
01:01:58.539 --> 01:02:03.099
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: That was a couple of years ago, the, um, the head wind.

1157
01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:00.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1158
01:02:03.099 --> 01:02:06.340
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: We've not had anything like that in the last couple of years, thankfully.

1159
01:02:06.340 --> 01:02:10.840
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So, but I mean, it's just, 0 yeah, yeah, he still loves to climb.

1160
01:02:07.500 --> 01:02:08.820
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Is he still a climber?

1161
01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:15.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, I was going to say maybe would that scare him that like, oh, this happened after I climbed, but probably not, no.

1162
01:02:12.159 --> 01:02:15.340
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: No, no, no, no.

1163
01:02:15.340 --> 01:02:17.980
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: The only thing he's really scared of just now is dogs.

1164
01:02:17.980 --> 01:02:20.559
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Um, we've never figured out why.

1165
01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:18.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1166
01:02:20.559 --> 01:02:23.320
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He's didn't have any big incident with dogs.

1167
01:02:23.320 --> 01:02:26.019
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: It's just like he just doesn't seem to trust them.

1168
01:02:26.380 --> 01:02:34.119
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And I kind of get it because like they're so the way that dogs act is so unpredictable.

1169
01:02:27.500 --> 01:02:29.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: The vibes are off for the dog.

1170
01:02:34.500 --> 01:02:35.159
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Well, that's it.

1171
01:02:35.159 --> 01:02:39.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: You don't know if they're if they're in bark, if they're allowed, you know, if they're,

1172
01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:38.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Mm-hmm.

1173
01:02:39.420 --> 01:02:41.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, there's different ways that it could go.

1174
01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:44.820
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So if he's aware of a dog, he will keep his eye on it the whole time.

1175
01:02:44.820 --> 01:02:46.800
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And he has this love-hate relationship with him.

1176
01:02:46.800 --> 01:02:50.219
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He does not want to get near them, but he also kind of wants to pet them.

1177
01:02:50.500 --> 01:02:54.340
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Admire from afar.

1178
01:02:51.360 --> 01:03:02.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So it's like, yeah, so it's like my, my sister has a, has a dog, so we've kind of been trying to, to get him to interact with, with Nugget a few times.

1179
01:03:02.400 --> 01:03:04.139
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And we've got there.

1180
01:03:02.500 --> 01:03:03.579
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh, nugget.

1181
01:03:04.139 --> 01:03:17.519
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: We've managed to get him to stroke her a couple of times, but she's also quite a yappy, fast moving dog and so like he'll come up and then she'll start moving and he's like, run away because like she dared to move.

1182
01:03:16.500 --> 01:03:17.460
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1183
01:03:17.460 --> 01:03:19.500
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Wait a minute, yeah.

1184
01:03:19.500 --> 01:03:20.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1185
01:03:19.559 --> 01:03:27.059
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: If we're at, if we're out somewhere and there's dogs, he will like keep stay close to you and like use you as a human shield.

1186
01:03:27.059 --> 01:03:29.280
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: But if the dog gets too close he will climb you.

1187
01:03:29.579 --> 01:03:32.219
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And I'm not.

1188
01:03:30.500 --> 01:03:31.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1189
01:03:32.219 --> 01:03:33.239
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I'm not exaggerating

1190
01:03:33.239 --> 01:03:41.460
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He will literally climb up, he will use the clothes as hand handholds and footholds, and he will get up as high as he can so that he is not near that dog.

1191
01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:41.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Wow.

1192
01:03:43.320 --> 01:03:45.179
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Oh, dear.

1193
01:03:45.179 --> 01:03:47.280
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: No, yeah, so he still climbs.

1194
01:03:47.280 --> 01:03:50.639
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: He did not put him off him, thankfully, but.

1195
01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:48.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1196
01:03:48.659 --> 01:03:49.619
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Okay.

1197
01:03:50.639 --> 01:03:54.179
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Okay, let's talk about the games because there's a few different games that you do.

1198
01:03:53.500 --> 01:03:54.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Sure.

1199
01:03:54.179 --> 01:03:55.980
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: What was your favourite game?

1200
01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:57.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I love the bird watching.

1201
01:03:58.000 --> 01:03:58.840
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Hmm.

1202
01:03:58.840 --> 01:04:04.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: You know, that was the that was the one when I finished last because it took me a while to actually understand what it was asking me to do.

1203
01:03:59.500 --> 01:04:00.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1204
01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:08.059
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh, I had a hard time finding the woodpecker.

1205
01:04:08.059 --> 01:04:09.980
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Um, that was the last one.

1206
01:04:08.500 --> 01:04:09.340
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Hmm.

1207
01:04:09.340 --> 01:04:11.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: That was a good one.

1208
01:04:09.980 --> 01:04:17.719
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I really liked it because, um, it forces you to pay closer attention to what's around and use your ears.

1209
01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:18.199
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, that's my problem.

1210
01:04:17.719 --> 01:04:19.219
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh.

1211
01:04:19.639 --> 01:04:23.300
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, because they're kind of like some of them you can kind of see.

1212
01:04:23.300 --> 01:04:26.300
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But other ones, uh, you have to just listen.

1213
01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:24.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1214
01:04:26.300 --> 01:04:29.420
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: But yeah, I'm surprised too, because I would I'm more of a visual person.

1215
01:04:29.420 --> 01:04:32.539
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And I thought, I don't know if you noticed all the bugs that were flying around.

1216
01:04:32.500 --> 01:04:33.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yep.

1217
01:04:32.539 --> 01:04:36.920
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I thought there was going to be something with the butterflies and the other bugs, but there wasn't.

1218
01:04:33.400 --> 01:04:35.500
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yep Yep.

1219
01:04:35.500 --> 01:04:37.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1220
01:04:36.920 --> 01:04:38.780
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, what was your favourite?

1221
01:04:39.500 --> 01:04:50.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Ooh, I liked the, I liked the scavenger hunt. Because I liked the kind of the, the link that you were doing there going from place to place.

1222
01:04:50.500 --> 01:04:57.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, I felt like that one should have been like, would be a good one to do 1st because it showed you all around the, The camp.

1223
01:04:55.500 --> 01:04:56.400
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Mm-hmm.

1224
01:04:56.400 --> 01:04:57.840
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1225
01:04:57.840 --> 01:04:59.699
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah, no, I enjoyed that.

1226
01:04:59.699 --> 01:05:00.840
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So we've got the scavenger hunt.

1227
01:05:00.840 --> 01:05:10.980
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Basically, you've got one, each of the characters has a game, basically, um, that they want to play with you. And so you you walk up to them and you say play and then they will tell you what their game is and then you can, you can do that.

1228
01:05:10.980 --> 01:05:22.500
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So, um, there was the scavenger hunt, which is you uh, have a clue and you had to show the other person where you think the clue was leading you towards.

1229
01:05:22.500 --> 01:05:24.539
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Some of them were easier than others, shall we say?

1230
01:05:25.739 --> 01:05:29.940
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So of course, for that, you, as you say, you need to have been everywhere.

1231
01:05:29.940 --> 01:05:31.800
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: so you need to have got the symbols for everything.

1232
01:05:32.340 --> 01:05:49.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And then there was the bird watching, and for that, you needed to find a bird, look at it through your binoculars, and once you've seen it through the binoculars, you'll get the symbol for that bird and you had to go back and tell the person what bird you saw and where you saw them.

1233
01:05:48.500 --> 01:05:50.659
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: And honestly, I didn't pay enough attention.

1234
01:05:50.659 --> 01:05:53.719
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So like I knew which bird, but then I would, I forgot where I'd see it.

1235
01:05:53.719 --> 01:05:55.519
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: So I just cycled through all of them.

1236
01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:57.002
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Yeah.

1237
01:05:55.519 --> 01:05:57.920
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I don't remember exactly where.

1238
01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:02.900
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Um, and then there was hide and seek.

1239
01:06:02.900 --> 01:06:07.519
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So there's a character who hides under a box and you have to go and find him.

1240
01:06:07.519 --> 01:06:09.920
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: I don't think there was anything else to that.

1241
01:06:09.920 --> 01:06:13.502
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: You just had to say play and you would go and hide and then you'd go find it.

1242
01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:11.502
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Oh, I think.

1243
01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:19.940
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: See, I thought I was doing it wrong because I'm like, do I just infinitely follow him? And then eventually it's like, no, we're pals now.

1244
01:06:17.860 --> 01:06:20.440
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Eventually it stops, yeah.

1245
01:06:19.940 --> 01:06:21.019
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah.

1246
01:06:20.500 --> 01:06:23.800
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: And then there was the art.

1247
01:06:23.800 --> 01:06:26.619
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: So there was an artist who wanted inspiration.

1248
01:06:24.500 --> 01:06:25.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yes.

1249
01:06:26.619 --> 01:06:31.480
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: The funny thing is about this is what I find...

1250
01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:31.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: I had a soft spot for her because her name was Gwenny.

1251
01:06:31.480 --> 01:06:37.599
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Okay, what I found particularly funny about that was basically every location is inspiration.

1252
01:06:38.380 --> 01:06:42.940
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Because it's like, I was like, oh, what are going to be the most inspirational places?

1253
01:06:38.500 --> 01:06:40.002
<v 75AE8ACE-FE15-4280-8B00-188C37215357>Chelsea: Yeah, that's true.

1254
01:06:42.940 --> 01:06:49.360
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: Oh, go to the beach and then it's like, oh, go to the, and then I'd gone through all the ones that I thought were inspirational and I was like, I've not finished this yet.

1255
01:06:49.360 --> 01:06:50.380
<v AF2CBEBB-3493-475E-82E9-7A7A0C03AAF3>Al: There's still ones to do.

